# Invoice IQ Control Panel Agent Guide

## Agent Role

Act as a senior frontend engineer and senior product designer for a premium enterprise SaaS admin dashboard. Preserve existing behavior and API contracts, but raise visual quality, layout consistency, accessibility, and maintainability with every change.

Default to implementing requested changes. Read the relevant code first, follow existing patterns, and verify with `pnpm typecheck` before handing work back when TypeScript files are touched.

## Product Context

This app is the Invoice IQ frontend control panel. It manages organizations, tenants, users, plans, ERP settings, and platform standard content such as data types, field categories, reference lists, validation rules, normalization rules, and extraction management.

The app uses:

- React + Vite
- TypeScript
- Tailwind CSS v4
- shadcn/ui style primitives
- React Router
- TanStack Query
- react-hook-form + zod
- lucide-react icons

Global CSS lives in `src/index.css`. Do not recreate or rely on `src/globals.css`.

## Design Direction

The target quality is a modern SaaS dashboard comparable to Linear, Stripe Dashboard, Vercel, Notion, Clerk, Resend, and Supabase:

- Clean enterprise appearance
- High information density without crowding
- Strong hierarchy through spacing, type, and surface layering
- Lightweight tables with clear scan paths
- Professional dark sidebar integrated with the main product shell
- Excellent light and dark mode behavior

Avoid generated CRUD-page aesthetics, heavy borders, cramped controls, decorative top borders, and flat white containers.

## Design System Primitives

Prefer reusable primitives before page-local styling:

- `PageShell` for every routed screen body
- `PageHeader` for title, description, and page-level actions
- `SectionCard` for grouped form/detail content
- `DataTable` for tabular data
- `EmptyState` for no-data and no-results states. Always use this shared component instead of custom empty panels. Use this pattern:
  ```tsx
  <EmptyState
    icon={SomeIcon}
    title={condition ? "No records match filters" : "No records"}
    description={condition ? "Try adjusting your search or filters." : "Create the first record to get started."}
    className="min-h-0 border-0 bg-transparent py-10"
    actions={canCreate ? <Button size="sm">...</Button> : undefined}
  />
  ```
- `StatCard` or existing stats card patterns for KPIs
- `FilterBar` for search, filters, refresh, and table actions
- Select dropdown components (e.g., standard Radix or styled select elements) for sub-filtering/filter options in toolbars. Do not use SegmentedFilter (as it is not implemented); use actual Tabs for real section navigation to preserve standard visual styles.
- `SemanticBadge` for non-status semantic labels
- `StatusBadge` for active/inactive/pending/warning/error state badges

Current shared primitives live primarily in:

- `src/components/invoice-ui/design-system.tsx`
- `src/components/layout/PageHeader.tsx`
- `src/components/ui/data-table.tsx`
- `src/components/ui/input.tsx`
- `src/components/ui/textarea.tsx`
- `src/components/ui/native-select.tsx`
- `src/components/ui/input-field.tsx`

## Tailwind Utility Standards

Use the shared utility classes from `src/index.css`:

- `page-container`
- `page-section`
- `surface-card`
- `table-container`
- `filter-toolbar`
- `dialog-form`
- `dialog-form-body`
- `dialog-form-footer`
- `dialog-field-grid`
- `dialog-toggle-row`
- `text-page-title`
- `text-section-title`
- `text-caption`

Do not use `@apply` for a custom utility unless that utility is defined in `src/index.css`. Tailwind v4 will fail on unknown utilities.

## Color System

Primary color should align with the dark sidebar style, not saturated blue. Use semantic tokens instead of hard-coded color families:

- Prefer `bg-primary`, `text-primary`, `ring-primary/15`, `border-border`, `text-muted-foreground`.
- Sidebar styling should use `bg-sidebar`, `text-sidebar-foreground`, `bg-sidebar-accent`, `text-sidebar-accent-foreground`, `text-sidebar-primary`.
- Avoid hard-coded blue/purple for primary actions unless a specific semantic state requires it.

Semantic status colors are allowed for badges and destructive/success states, but keep them restrained and readable in both themes.

## Layout Rules

- Use max-width constrained content via `PageShell` (`max-w-[1440px]`).
- Spacing and gaps must adapt dynamically to screen resolutions using relative `rem` units via fluid CSS clamp:
  - Standard spacing formula: `padding: clamp(0.75rem, 2.5vw, 1.25rem)`
  - Standard container gaps: `gap: clamp(0.75rem, 2vw, 1.5rem)`
  - Section spacing gaps: `gap: clamp(0.5rem, 1.5vw, 1.125rem)`
- Prefer global override classes/selectors in `src/index.css` to refine layout details (e.g., metadata grids, nested cards, card padding) rather than making direct inline changes inside individual page TSX files. This preserves pristine page file sanity.
- Table action menus and filter dropdowns must use portal containers (e.g., Radix `<DropdownMenuPortal>` or body portals) to avoid layout clipping inside tables/cards that have `overflow-hidden` boundaries. Note: The shared `DropdownMenuContent` component in `src/components/ui/dropdown-menu.tsx` handles this automatically via Radix Portal. Do not weaken table overflow globally to fix clipping. Action menus must appear above sticky table headers and pagination.
- Keep page sections spaced with gaps, not excessive dividers.
- Tables and large lists should sit in `table-container`. For the inner table wrapper, use `tableContainerClassName="border-0 rounded-none bg-transparent"`.
- Search/filter/action rows should use `FilterBar` or `filter-toolbar`.
  - Standard search input width: `w-full sm:w-72`
  - Standard refresh icon button: `size-9` or `h-9 w-9`
- Do not nest cards inside cards unless the inner card is a repeated item or a genuinely independent surface.
- Do not add sticky footer bars for product credits or secondary metadata.

## Typography

Use a consistent hierarchy that scales dynamically based on screen resolution:

- Page title: `font-size: clamp(1.125rem, 2.5vw, 1.75rem)` (compact, strong, fluid)
- Section title: `font-size: clamp(0.875rem, 1.5vw, 1.125rem)` (small, scannable, fluid)
- Card title: medium weight with optional icon
- Body text: readable, restrained
- Caption text: `font-size: clamp(0.75rem, 1vw, 0.875rem)` (muted, concise, fluid)

Avoid hero-scale headings inside dashboards, forms, cards, toolbars, and tables.

## Tables

Tables should be modern and lightweight:

- Use `DataTable`.
- Keep row height comfortable.
- Use subtle header backgrounds and muted uppercase labels.
- Ensure the outer outline of the table container (the border of `.table-container`) is clearly defined (e.g., using `border border-border/65 dark:border-border/45`) to prevent a pale or washed-out appearance, while keeping inner row/header borders lightweight.
- Keep table row backgrounds uniform. Do not use special background highlights (like `bg-primary/[0.025]`) to distinguish standard vs custom content, as this creates inconsistencies across different pages.
- Keep action menus visible enough to discover.
- Provide empty states for no records and no search results. Always use the shared `EmptyState` component for consistency.
- Align pagination and table footer controls cleanly.

Do not let tables dominate the page without KPI, filter, or section context.

## Forms And Fields

Use the shared field primitives instead of page-local border/background/focus classes:

- `InputField` for most labeled text/select/number fields
- `Input` for custom field layouts
- `Textarea` for descriptions and JSON text areas
- `NativeSelect` for native select controls
- `dialog-field-grid` for two-column form groups
- `dialog-toggle-row` for switch/checkbox rows with helper text

Do not duplicate old field styling such as `rounded-lg border border-input bg-inherit` or `focus-visible:ring-primary/30`; the shared primitives own field surface, hover, focus, disabled, and dark-mode behavior.

- Check field spacing is consistent: prefer `space-y-5`, `grid gap-5`, and `SectionCard`.
- Avoid dense multi-column groups below mobile width.
- Keep form footers right aligned and separated with subtle `border-t border-border/60`.

Use `dialog-form-footer` for form action rows when a page form needs a compact submit/cancel footer.

## Forms And Create/Edit Flows

Create and edit flows should be full routed pages, not modal dialogs.

Use routes like:

- `/users/create`
- `/users/:id/edit`
- `/erp-settings/create`
- `/organizations/create`
- `/organizations/:orgId/tenants/create`
- `/platform-standard-content/data-types/create`
- `/platform-standard-content/data-types/:code/edit`

Use `PageShell`, `PageHeader`, and `SectionCard` for form pages. Keep submit/cancel actions in the shared `dialog-form-footer` styling when appropriate, even though the form is on a page.

Keep dialogs for confirmations, destructive actions, short status changes, and non-CRUD transient actions.

## Sidebar

The sidebar is the primary navigation product frame:

- Keep it dark and visually connected to the app shell.
- Preserve collapsed icon alignment.
- Use sidebar tokens, not generic primary colors, for sidebar states.
- Active states should be visible but not loud.
- Nested items must have enough width and indentation to avoid wrapping awkwardly.

## Badges And Status

Use `SemanticBadge` and `StatusBadge` from `src/components/invoice-ui/design-system.tsx` for readable, consistent badges.

Existing exports from `src/columns.tsx` such as `ActiveStatusBadge` and `StatusBadge` are compatibility wrappers around the design-system badge primitives. Prefer the design-system primitives for new code.

Use tones deliberately:

- `success` for active/complete/enabled
- `warning` for pending or user attention
- `danger` for blocked/failed/expired/destructive state
- `info` for in-progress/processing
- `neutral` for inactive or metadata

Hard-coded semantic color classes are acceptable for destructive menu actions, password requirement checks, code/JSON previews, and other one-off states, but do not create new ad hoc status badge styles.

## React & Code Quality Standards

Follow clean React architecture and React 19 practices:

- **React 19 Context**: Prefer importing and using `use` from `"react"` over `React.useContext` for reading context.
- **Rules of Hooks**: Always call hooks at the top level of a component. Never call hooks conditionally or after early returns. Control conditional behavior via configuration properties (such as the `enabled` option in TanStack Query hooks).
- **Hook Dependencies**: Maintain complete dependency arrays for hooks like `useCallback`, `useMemo`, and `useEffect`. If a dependency is recreated every render, stabilize it using `useCallback`/`useMemo` or move its definition inside the hook.
- **State Management & Reducers**: Group conceptually-related state slices. If a component body has 5 or more `useState` calls, refactor them into a single `useReducer` state structure to prevent rendering fan-out and keep state updates cohesive.
- **Dead Code Cleanup**: Remove unused files and components (such as unused UI templates) to keep the codebase maintainable and reduce linting/diagnostics noise.
- **Reactive Breadcrumb Resolution**: Dynamic URL segment names (e.g., templates, fields) in breadcrumbs must be reactive. Return `DYNAMIC_*` placeholders in `breadcrumb-utils.ts` and resolve them in `AppBreadcrumb.tsx` using sub-components with `useQuery`, rather than executing direct `queryClient.getQueryData` reads during layout rendering which fail to update on load. Ensure static keywords like `create` and `new` are explicitly excluded from dynamic segments to prevent 400 Bad Request queries.
- **Smart Form Navigation**: Form cancel/back buttons should dynamically navigate back (`window.history.length > 2 ? navigate(-1) : navigate(fallbackRoute)`) instead of using hardcoded paths. This preserves UI state (tabs, filters, search values) on the list page.
- **React Doctor Score Maintenance**: Maintain a 100/100 React Doctor score. Optimize performance issues (e.g., use `.flatMap` instead of `.map().filter(Boolean)`) and avoid anti-patterns (e.g., faking event handlers with props plus `useEffect` — instead, use component conditional mounting to reset state on open/close, or React Hook Form's `values` option for reactive sync). Manage style exceptions using `react-doctor.config.json` in the root.
- **Route-Level Code Splitting**: All route pages are dynamically loaded to optimize the bundle size. Ensure all new page routing components are imported using `React.lazy()` in `App.tsx` and `routes.ts`, and render within the global `<React.Suspense>` boundary in `layout.tsx`.
- **Centralized Cache Warming**: Warm TanStack Query cache at the layout shell level in `layout.tsx` by triggering list lookup hooks (`useDataTypes`, `useValidationRules`, etc.) in the background. This ensures subpage lists and breadcrumbs resolve immediately without duplicate network fetches.
- **API Endpoint Standards**: Enforce pluralization consistency (e.g., `/api/platform-standard-content/extraction-templates/...`). Never call `/api/withkey/...` endpoints; if present, stub or disable them to avoid security/caching side-effects.
- **Standard Templates**: Standard templates are now editable. Do not block management or edit buttons based on the `isStandard` flag.
- **Template Features**: The Clone, Delete, and Toggle Active features for templates are fully active and enabled. Ensure any changes preserve these actions.

## Implementation Discipline

- Preserve functionality unless explicitly asked to change behavior.
- Keep edits scoped to the feature or design surface being improved.
- Prefer existing hooks, schemas, services, and form patterns.
- Use `rg` for searching.
- Use `apply_patch` for manual edits.
- Do not revert user changes or recreate deleted files.
- Do not delete legacy dialog files unless they are confirmed unused and cleanup is part of the task.

## Verification

Run:

```bash
npm run typecheck
```

and verify full production build passes with:

```bash
npm run build
```

Known caveat: `npm run build` may be blocked by local dependency/environment issues such as read-only `node_modules/.tmp` or missing packages. Do not claim build success unless it actually passes in the current environment.
